er, George VI, to the throne, fate began to shape the paths of the brothers who were not born into an ordinary family. The relationship between Elizabeth and Margaret was now much more than sisterhood.\\r\\n\\r\\nA difficult process awaits Elizabeth II in her journey as the royal heir and then queen, in which she must determine her priorities and distinguish the needs of her family and the royal family. On the other hand, Princess Margaret had her own problems in family, royalty and social life.\\r\\nHe must discover his role and learn to live his life in the shadow of his brother. Award-winning biographer Andrew Morton successfully captures the relationship between the sisters with authoritative references. Beyond the private lives of two noble figures, it reveals the human side of a ruler and living in the shadow of a ruler.\\r\\n\\r\\n*Morton presents the coldness of royal life with a rich text. Margaret\'s story unfolds.* ?New York Times\\r\\n\\r\\n*A meticulous and well-researched study of the sisters\' closeness and their invisible but understandably contradictory relationship.*\\r\\n?Wall Street Journal\\r\\n\\r\\n*Delightfully detailed, partly gossipy, generally impressive\\u2026 A detailed examination of the noble sisters is sure to be very\\r\\nwill attract attention.* ?Booklist\\r\\n\\r\\n*Morton\'s illuminating analysis of the complex relationship between Queen Elizabeth II and Princess Margaret manages to humanely address the myths surrounding these two highly public figures. It will appeal to history buffs, biography readers and especially fans of The Crown.* ?Library Journal\\r\\n\\r\\n*Biographer Morton examines the vivid history of the \'ebb and flow of relationship, deep love and primitive jealousy\' between Queen Elizabeth II and her sister, Princess Margaret. Those interested in the royal family will be fascinated.* ?Publishers Weekly\",\"ru\":\"\\u0410\\u0432\\u0442\\u043e\\u0440 \\u0431\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0441\\u0435\\u043b\\u043b\\u0435\\u