order to gain an advantage against adversaries even today, the importance of human-based intelligence provided by people such as agents, spies and informants has been known since the earliest periods of history. There are narratives in the Old Testament and in The Art of War, written by the Chinese philosopher Sun Tzu, who is thought to have lived around 500 BC, that emphasize the importance of espionage and intelligence activities. In later times, the importance of intelligence as an active part of the established system in achieving the military and political goals of the state and eliminating internal and external threats was perhaps best understood by the Byzantine Empire.\\r\\nIn summary, the Byzantines, who had an extremely complex and organized intelligence system, gained superiority over their opponents and enemies thanks to the good functioning of this system. Byzantine emperors, who benefited greatly from the advantages provided by these intelligence and espionage activities, on the one hand, neutralized threats and attacks from inside and outside; On the other hand, they were able to make plans to achieve their foreign policy goals. It turns out all this worked; The Byzantine Empire, which lived much longer than its neighbors and enemies, was able to maintain its existence for a long time thanks to its extremely effective and active intelligence and smart policies.\",\"ru\":\"\\u0425\\u043e\\u0442\\u044f \\u0438\\u043d\\u0442\\u0435\\u0440\\u043f\\u0440\\u0435\\u0442\\u0430\\u0446\\u0438\\u0438, \\u043f\\u043e\\u043b\\u0443\\u0447\\u0435\\u043d\\u043d\\u044b\\u0435 \\u0438\\u0437 \\u0441\\u043d\\u043e\\u0432, \\u043f\\u0440\\u043e\\u0440\\u043e\\u0447\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432, \\u0431\\u043e\\u0436\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u0435\\u043d\\u043d\\u044b\\u0445 \\u0437\\u043d\\u0430\\u043a\\u043e\\u0432 \\u0438\\u043b\\u0438 \\u0430\\u0441\\u0442\\u0440\\u043e\\u043b\\u043e\\u0433\\u0438\\u0447\\u0435\\u0441\\u043a\\u0438\\u0445 \\u043f\\u0440\\u0435\\u